    <stitle>530 and DT-466/408 Diesel Engine Service (1994) - VIBRATION DAMPER, CRANKSHAFT, MAIN BEARINGS, FLYWHEEL AND
        CRANKCASE - CRANKCASE (Reconditioning)
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcsubsec>
        <title>CRANKCASE (Reconditioning)</title>
        <svcproc svcproctype="clean" graphiccount="2">
            <title>CLEANING</title>
            <svcprocinfo>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>The best way to clean the crankcase during engine overhaul is in a chemical bath or "HOT
                            TANK". This removes all carbonous material and mineral deposits which collect in the cooling
                            passages. If the "HOT TANK" is not available, use the following cleaning procedure.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </svcprocinfo>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Clean all old gasket material from the machined surfaces of the crankcase using a
                    scraper and a sanding block.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Clean the cylinder sleeve bores using soap, water and a nylon brush.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove main oil gallery cup plug, located at rear of crankcase by using a hammer and
                    chisel, knockout the main oil galley plug (
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050744">7.44</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">With the plugs removed from the crankcase, clean the crankcase as follows:</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">a nylon brush with soap and water to clean the oil galleries.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Clean the cross drillings using a nylon brush with soap and water. (
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050745">7.45</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        )
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Blow out all oil galleries and cross drillings using filtered compressed air.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Clean all threaded holes using a tap of appropriate size.</para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install new main oil gallery cup plug as follows:</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Clean mating surfaces on plug and crankcase.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Apply Loctite(r) 262 to the outside edge of the cup plug.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Drive the cup plug in using an arbor approximately 1/4 in. (6mm) smaller in diameter
                        than the plug being installed.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Recess the plug 1/8 inch (3.2mm).</para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install new pipe plug into rear of crankcase.</para>
                <figure id="ef1050744" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg2391" filename="../figeg2/EG2391.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 7.44.</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. Oil Galley Plug</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. Crankcase</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. Chisel</callout1>
                        <callout1>4. Hammer</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef1050745" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg3058" filename="../figeg3/EG3058.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 7.45.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
